findings.message:
Three exported classes, a Factory, and an inheritance tree to dispatch on six hardcoded coupon codes. The PR justifies this with "so we can add more coupon types later" — but you can add coupon types to a plain data table just as easily, and you'll know the right abstraction only when you have two or three real examples. Right now this is YAGNI in a tuxedo. Replace the whole module with a lookup table and one function:
```ts
const COUPONS: Record<string, { kind: 'percent' | 'flat'; value: number }> = {
  WELCOME10: { kind: 'percent', value: 0.10 },
  FIVEOFF:   { kind: 'flat',    value: 500  },
  // ...
};
export function applyCoupon(amount: number, code: string | undefined): number {
  if (!code) return amount;
  const coupon = COUPONS[code];
  if (!coupon) return amount;
  return coupon.kind === 'percent'
    ? Math.floor(amount * (1 - coupon.value))
    : Math.max(0, amount - coupon.value);
}
```
Three files reduced to one, easier to read, easier to extend when you actually need to.
